        <p id="Par20">A negative binomial is a generalization of a Poisson regression that allows the variance to be different from the mean, shaped by the dispersion parameter <italic>Î¸</italic>. There are two alternative forms of parameterization for a negative binomialâNB1 and NB2âwhich were first introduced by Cameron and Trivedi [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR36">36</xref>]. The difference between NB1 and NB2 is in the conditional variance of <italic>y</italic><sub><italic>i</italic></sub>. Assuming <italic>y</italic><sub><italic>i</italic></sub> has mean <italic>Î»</italic><sub><italic>i</italic></sub>, the general variance function follows the form <italic>Ï</italic><sub><italic>i</italic></sub>â=â<italic>Î»</italic><sub><italic>i</italic></sub>â+â<italic>Î±Î»</italic><sub><italic>i</italic></sub><sup><italic>p</italic></sup>, where <italic>Î±</italic> is a scalar parameter. NB1 uses <italic>p</italic>â=â1, whereas NB2 uses the quadratic form of variance with <italic>p</italic>â=â2. We use the most common implementation of the negative binomial, NB2, hereafter. The variance for the NB2 model is given as</p>
